        <div class="mt-8 text-center border-t border-outline-variant/30 pt-6">
          <p class="text-[13px] leading-relaxed italic text-on-surface-variant max-w-3xl mx-auto">
            <strong class="text-on-surface font-sans not-italic">Figure 1:</strong> Eigenvalue spectra for FCC (top) and BCC (bottom) potentials. The near-linear decay in log-space (dashed lines) visually corroborates the quantitative hyper-ribbon dimensionality (PR &lt; 1.5) observed across all evaluated physical models, proving that prediction errors are tightly constrained to a low-dimensional manifold.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>4.2 Bootstrap Confidence Intervals</h3>
      <p>Figure 2 displays PR with 95% CIs. All intervals exclude the maximal dimensionality (3.0), confirming sub-manifold structure.</p>

      <h3>4.3 Simpson's Paradox in BCC Data</h3>
      <p is:raw>Figure 3 demonstrates the paradox: pooled correlation between \(C_{11}\) and \(C_{12}\) errors is \(r = -0.435\), while within-group correlations average \(r_w = +0.147\). 57% of material-level correlations have the opposite sign from the pooled estimate.</p>

      <h3>4.4 Meta-Analysis of Cross-Material Transferability</h3>
      <p is:raw>Figure 4 shows the forest plot. Random-effects summary \(\bar{y}_{RE} = -0.18\) (95% CI: [−0.42, 0.06]). Heterogeneity \(I^2 = 91.4\%\), \(\tau = 0.476\), indicating that most variance is between-material rather than within-material.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="manuscript-section mt-12">
      <h2>5. Discussion</h2>
      <p is:raw>The hyper-ribbon geometry has three implications for universal potential design. First, because the effective dimensionality is ~1.4 in a 3D property space, a universal potential needs to correctly model only one or two dominant error modes—not every property independently. Second, the Simpson's paradox warns against pooling errors across crystal structures without stratification: a potential that appears superior in aggregate may be inferior within each subgroup. Third, the high \(I^2\) implies that material-specific fine-tuning will outperform a single global fit.</p>
      <p is:raw>Our framework is extensible: additional properties (phonons, defects, surfaces) increase ambient dimensionality \(m\) but need not increase effective dimensionality if they lie in the same ribbon. Future work will test this conjecture on amorphous and multi-component systems.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="manuscript-section mt-12">
      <h2>6. Conclusions</h2>
      <p>We have shown that IP error manifolds are hyper-ribbons: low-dimensional structures embedded in high-dimensional property spaces. The geometric framework—combining PCA, bootstrap uncertainty, paradox detection, and meta-analysis—provides quantitative diagnostics for potential selection that go beyond traditional pointwise comparisons. These tools are implemented in the open-source <code>atlas-distill</code> engine.</p>
    </section>

